[[File:Diplusodon decussatus00.jpg|thumb|<center>''Diplusodon decussatus'' from 'Sertum Plantarum']]
'''Mary Maria Fielding''' (''née'' '''Simpson'''; 25 January 1804 – 22 February 1895), baptised on 22 May 1804, was a British [[Botany|botanist]] and botanical illustrator.<ref name="Desmond1994">{{cite book|first=Ray|last= Desmond|title=Dictionary Of British And Irish Botanists And Horticulturists|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=thmPzIltAV8C&pg=PA245|year= 1994|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-0-85066-843-8|page=245}}</ref> She was the daughter of John Simpson, a merchant from Lancaster. <ref>https://archiveshub.jisc.ac.uk/search/archives/df6546b0-4971-3b50-a774-2139edd5c2f0</ref> She was the wife of fellow botanist [[Henry Barron Fielding|Henry Fielding]], whom she married in Liverpool on 21 December 1826. A native of [[Lancaster, Lancashire]],  between 1830 and 1833 she produced six volumes of botanical watercolours which have been cited as an "important source for the study of the county's flora in the early nineteenth century".<ref name="ODNB"/> The volumes, consisting of about 530 botanical watercolours<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bodley.ox.ac.uk/dept/scwmss/wmss/online/1500-1900/fielding/fielding.html|title=Fielding Water Colours|website=www.bodley.ox.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=15 November 2017}}</ref> ended up in Oxford University and in thanks the university gave her brother an M.A.<ref name="ODNB"/> In 1843, Fielding, her husband Henry, and [[George Gardner (botanist)|George Gardner]], published ''Sertum plantarum'', which Mary produced illustrated descriptions for, documenting some 75 new or rare plants. She lived in Church Street, Lancaster in her last decades.<ref name="ODNB"> {{citation |last=Jackson |first=B. D.  |title=Fielding, Henry Borron |work=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |edition=online |year=2005 |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/9401/102426|publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=15 November 2017}} {{ODNBsub}}</ref> 

