'''Roaring Jack''' was an [[Australia]]n [[Celtic punk]]/[[folk punk]] [[rock band|band]] of the 1980s and 1990s. The band formed in 1985 and played their first shows in [[Sydney]] in 1986. Original members were [[Alistair Hulett]] ([[acoustic guitar]] and [[vocals]]),{{cn|date=November 2018}} Dave Williams (bass), Steve Thompson (drums), Bob (Rab) Mannell (electric guitar and bouzouki) and Hunter Owens (accordion/mandolin and vocals).{{cn|date=November 2018}}

Owens was later replaced by Steven (Steph) Miller on the same instruments and on vocals.{{cn|date=November 2018}} Rod Gilchrist replaced Steve Thompson on drums after the recording of their first album.{{cn|date=November 2018}} The band was nominated for two [[ARIA Music Awards]] during their career.<ref name=Alistair>[http://www.folkicons.co.uk/alisbio.htm Alistair's Biography] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060615022312/http://www.folkicons.co.uk/alisbio.htm |date=15 June 2006 }} ''Folk Icons''. Accessed 30 January 2010.</ref>

The band built a cult following by playing the [[Sydney]] [[public house|pub]] circuit eventually scoring regular slots at the Harold Park Hotel in [[Glebe, New South Wales|Glebe]] and the [[Sandringham Hotel, Newtown|Sandringham Hotel]] in [[Newtown, New South Wales|Newtown]].{{cn|date=November 2018}} Their music had a strong political focus with emphasis on aboriginal Rights and [[trade union|union]] activism, working class activiism, anti authoritarianism, opposition to gentrification, and other social issues, as well as an emphasis on the pleasure of whiskey and drinking, having fun and cavorting.{{cn|date=November 2018}} In keeping with this the band gave many benefit performances for a diverse range of [[left wing politics|left wing]] causes with fellow rebel rousers [[The Urban Guerillas]], including the workers of [[Cockatoo Island, New South Wales|Cockatoo Island]], [[Sydney Hilton bombing|accused Sydney Hilton bomber Tim Anderson]] and opposition to the first [[Gulf War]].{{cn|date=November 2018}}

The band went on to support the likes of [[Billy Bragg]], the [[Pogues]] and [[The Men They Couldn't Hang]] during their Australian tours.{{cn|date=November 2018}}

Roaring Jack recorded for independent Sydney label Mighty Boy Records. They released the ''Street Celtability'' [[mini-LP]] in 1987, and ''Through The Smoke Of Innocence'' LP (1990).{{cn|date=November 2018}} German label Jump Up Records released all of these as ''The Complete Works'', a double CD package, in 2002.{{cn|date=November 2018}}

Some of their best remembered songs include 'Yuppie Town", "The lads from the B.L.F.", "the thin red line", ‘Buy Us A Drink’, ‘The Old Divide And Rule’, ‘Destitution Road’ and ‘We Don’t Play No Elton Fucking John’. A video was made for the single 'Framed', a song which raised awareness of the Campaign Exposing the Frame-Up of Tim Anderson.{{cn|date=November 2018}}

The band split in 1992{{cn|date=November 2018}}. Alistair Hulett then enjoyed a successful solo career as an internationally recognised folk musician.{{cn|date=November 2018}} Steph Miller formed his own band, The Wickermen in 1991 and spent most of the 1990s as a multi-instrumentalist in the successful Sydney band, Eva Trout.{{cn|date=November 2018}} Steph released a solo CD, Strange Sea, in 2004.{{cn|date=November 2018}}

Roaring Jack reformed briefly for two reunion gigs in 1995.{{cn|date=November 2018}} Alistair Hulett died of liver failure and cancer on 28 January 2010.<ref>http://www.talkawhile.co.uk/yabbse/index.php?topic=34027.0</ref><ref>http://mrzine.monthlyreview.org/2010/rovics290110.html</ref>

